and m_angle_ABC m_angle_BAC :: real
assumes h0 : "is_coplanar {A, B, C, D}"
and h1 : "is_isosceles_triangle B D C"
and h2 : "is_isosceles_triangle A C D"
and h3 : "m_angle_ABC = 70"
shows "m_angle_BAC = 35"
 proof- 
  show ?thesis sledgehammer

a_8_deepseek_solve_direct.formal solution:
(* ### Problem
 Triangles $BDC$ and $ACD$ are coplanar and isosceles. If we have $m\angle ABC = 70^\circ$, what is $m\angle BAC$, in degrees?

[asy]
unitsize(2 cm);

defaultpen(linewidth(1pt)+fontsize(10pt));
pair a,b,c,d;
b = (0,0);
c = (1,0);
d = c+dir(140);
a = d+dir(70);
draw(a--b--c--cycle);
draw(d--c);
pair s,t;
s = (.5,0)+(0,.05);
t = (.5,0)+(0,-.05);
draw(s--t);
s = .5*(c+d) + .05*dir(50);
t = .5*(c+d) - .05*dir(50);
draw(s--t);
s = .5*(a+d) + .05*dir(160);
t = .5*(a+d) - .05*dir(160);
draw(s--t);
label("A",a,N);
label("B",b,SW);
label("C",c,SE);
label("D",d,NW);
label("$70^\circ$",b+(.05,.03),NE);
[/asy] The final Answer is $35^\circ$
 ### Proof
 Since $\overline{BC}\cong\overline{DC}$, that means $\angle DBC\cong\angle BDC$ and $$m\angle DBC=m\angle BDC=70^\circ.$$ We see that $\angle BDC$ and $\angle ADC$ must add up to $180^\circ$, so $m\angle ADC=180-70=110^\circ$.
Triangle $ACD$ is an isosceles triangle, so the base angles must be equal. If the base angles each have a measure of $x^\circ$, then $m\angle ADC+2x=180^\circ.$  This gives us  $$110+2x=180,$$ so $2x=70$ and  $x=35.$  Since $\angle BAC$ is one of the base angles, it has a measure of $\boxed{35^\circ}$.
 *)

theorem
fixes mABC mBAC :: real
assumes h0 : "mABC = 70"
and h1 : "Triangle BDC is isosceles"
and h2 : "Triangle ACD is isosceles"
and h3 : "BDC and ACD are coplanar"
shows "mBAC = 35"
 proof- 
  show ?thesis sledgehammer

